  "properties": {
    "encrypted": "false",
    "title": "Plan a Pizza Party",
    "long_instructions": "<img src=\"https://images.code.org/fa50191ac64b4072e71210af83000541-pizza_party.jpg\" style=\"float: right; width: 150px; margin-left: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\">\r\n\r\nYou are planning a class pizza party and want to include music and activities.\r\n\r\nWhat information (data) would you want to collect to help make the party fun and successful?\r\n\r\n**Tip:** Think about food, drinks, supplies, music, number of people, or anything else that could help you plan.\r\n\r\n**Type your answer below.**\r\n",
    "teacher_markdown": "This activity introduces students to the idea that data is any information that can help solve a problem or answer a question. In this case, students are imagining they are planning a class pizza party and identifying what information (data) they might need to collect to make the event fun and successful.\r\n\r\nThis is an intentional pre-assessment — students haven’t formally learned what data is yet, so their responses will give insight into how they naturally think about information and decision-making. Remind students that there are no wrong answers. If they’re stuck, you can prompt them with questions like:\r\n\r\n    “What would you want to know before the party?”\r\n\r\n    “What kind of things would you need to plan for food, drinks, or activities?”\r\n\r\nEncourage a range of responses: number of people attending, pizza preferences, drink options, dietary needs, supplies, or even music or activity ideas.\r\n**Assessment Opportunity: Pre-Assessment**\r\n\r\nLooking at what data the students collect here can help you understand what previous understanding they have of data and the the role of data in solving real-world problems.",
